<h2 id="heading-0">The Tax Method That Costs You Money</h2>

<p>Most Texas business owners use the wrong accounting method. They're either:</p>

<ul>
<li>Stuck in cash basis when they should be accrual</li>
<li>Using accrual when cash basis would save them money</li>
<li>Unsure which to use (most common)</li>
</ul>

<p>The difference isn't just "how you record transactions." It's about real money - thousands of dollars in tax savings or extra payments.</p>

<p>Let me show you exactly how to choose and when to switch.</p>

<h2 id="heading-1">Cash Basis: Simple But Limited</h2>

<h3 id="heading-2">How It Works</h3>

<p>You record income when you receive payment. You record expenses when you pay them.</p>

<p><strong>Example:</strong> You send an invoice in December but don't get paid until January. Under cash basis, you don't record the income until January.</p>

<h3 id="heading-3">Who Should Use Cash Basis</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Small service businesses</strong> under $25 million revenue</li>
<li><strong>Simple operations</strong> with few inventory items</li>
<li><strong>Businesses that want simplicity</strong> over precision</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-4">Tax Advantages</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Defer income:</strong> Delay recognizing revenue by collecting payments later</li>
<li><strong>Accelerate deductions:</strong> Pay expenses early to reduce current year taxes</li>
<li><strong>Simple compliance:</strong> No complex adjustments needed</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="heading-2">Accrual Basis: Complex But Powerful</h2>

<h3 id="heading-3">How It Works</h3>

<p>You record income when you earn it (send invoice). You record expenses when you incur them (receive bill).</p>

<p><strong>Example:</strong> You send an invoice in December. Under accrual, you record the income in December, even if payment comes in January.</p>

<h3 id="heading-4">Who Must Use Accrual</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Public companies</strong> (required by law)</li>
<li><strong>Businesses over $25 million</strong> revenue (IRS requirement)</li>
<li><strong>Businesses with inventory</strong> (generally required)</li>
<li><strong>Any business that chooses it</strong> (with proper setup)</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-5">Tax Advantages</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Smooth income:</strong> Even revenue recognition prevents tax spikes</li>
<li><strong>Match expenses to revenue:</strong> Better profitability tracking</li>
<li><strong>Tax planning flexibility:</strong> More control over timing</li>
</ul>

