<h3 id="heading-8">When Cash Basis Saves You Money</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Growth years:</strong> Defer income to lower tax brackets</li>
<li><strong>High-expense years:</strong> Accelerate deductions</li>
<li><strong>Cash flow crunches:</strong> Delay tax payments</li>
<li><strong>Before selling:</strong> Minimize reported profits</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-9">When Accrual Basis Saves You Money</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Steady growth:</strong> Avoid tax bracket jumps</li>
<li><strong>Seasonal businesses:</strong> Smooth tax payments</li>
<li><strong>Inventory businesses:</strong> Match costs to sales</li>
<li><strong>Bank financing:</strong> Show consistent profits</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="heading-10">How to Switch Accounting Methods</h2>

<h3 id="heading-11">From Cash to Accrual</h3>

<ol>
<li><strong>Choose your cutoff date:</strong> Usually year-end</li>
<li><strong>Calculate adjustments:</strong> Accrue unpaid invoices and bills</li>
<li><strong>File Form 3115:</strong> IRS permission to change methods</li>
<li><strong>Update your books:</strong> One-time adjustment entries</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Tax Impact:</strong> May create additional taxable income in the transition year.</p>

<h3 id="heading-12">From Accrual to Cash</h3>

<ol>
<li><strong>Reverse accruals:</strong> Eliminate unpaid invoices and bills</li>
<li><strong>IRS approval:</strong> Form 3115 required</li>
<li><strong>One-time adjustment:</strong> Reduce taxable income</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Tax Impact:</strong> Usually creates a tax loss in the transition year.</p>

<h3 id="heading-13">The Automatic Change Rule</h3>

<p>If your average revenue is under $25 million for 3+ years, you can change methods without IRS permission. But you still need to file Form 3115.</p>

<h2 id="heading-14">Texas-Specific Tax Considerations</h2>

<h3 id="heading-15">Texas Margin Tax</h3>

<p>Texas has a 0.75% margin tax that follows federal accounting methods. Your choice affects both federal and state taxes.</p>

<h3 id="heading-16">Sales Tax Timing</h3>

<p>If you collect sales tax, accrual basis requires tracking it when earned, not when collected. This can create temporary differences between your books and tax payments.</p>

<h3 id="heading-17">Oil & Gas Considerations</h3>

<p>Texas energy businesses often use accrual for percentage depletion and complex revenue recognition rules.</p>

<h2 id="heading-18">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

<h3 id="heading-19">Mixing Methods</h3>

<p>Some businesses try to "pick and choose" - using accrual for expenses but cash for income. The IRS calls this "hybrid method" and it's generally not allowed without specific approval.</p>

<h3 id="heading-20">Ignoring Inventory Rules</h3>

<p>If you have inventory, you generally must use accrual basis. Cash basis inventory tracking leads to inaccurate cost of goods sold.</p>

<h3 id="heading-21">Late Changes</h3>

<p>Changing methods mid-year requires IRS permission and can be complicated. Plan changes at year-end.</p>

<h2 id="heading-22">Which Method is Right for You?</h2>

<h3 id="heading-23">Choose Cash Basis If:</h3>

<ul>
<li>Your revenue is under $5 million</li>
<li>You have simple operations</li>
<li>You want maximum tax deferral</li>
<li>Cash flow management is critical</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-24">Choose Accrual Basis If:</h3>

<ul>
<li>You have inventory</li>
<li>Your revenue exceeds $10 million</li>
<li>You want smooth tax payments</li>
<li>You need accurate financial statements for loans</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-25">The Hybrid Approach</h3>

<p>Some businesses use accrual for financial reporting but cash for tax purposes. This requires careful tracking and IRS approval.</p>

<h2 id="heading-26">The Bottom Line</h2>

<p>The right accounting method saves you money by matching your business needs with tax opportunities. Cash basis gives you control over timing. Accrual basis gives you accuracy and consistency.</p>

<p>Most Texas businesses should start with cash basis and switch to accrual when they hit $5-10 million in revenue or add inventory.</p>

<p>The key is understanding both methods and choosing based on your specific situation, not following what "everyone else does."</p>